<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>HOME AFFAIRS SELECT COMMITTEE</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt">Written evidence from Barry Coppinger, </span><br /><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt">Police and Crime Commissioner for Cleveland [PCC Progress 06]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1.0</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This submission is made to assist the HASC by providing information on the operation of the PCC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Cleveland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. It is set out according to the headings of the 6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> November announcement. Given that it is only one year since the introduction of PCCs, though there has been considerable work undertaken, there has been insufficient time to evaluate this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> work</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Of necessity considerable energy has been expended in building the foundations from which to operate in what is a wholly new landscape.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2.0</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The effectiveness of Commissioners in reducing crime and delivering an effective police force in their area.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Policing represents only part, albeit a very important part, of a collective effort to reduce crime. There is a wide diversity of work undertaken in this area, whether in prisons, by probation, by the ‘troubled families’ programmes, by police officers and others. PCCs have responsibility across the entire criminal justice landscape at a local level and so make considerable efforts to join the disparate parts of it together and make it as effective as possible. However given that each component of this complex system is being squeezed financially, the gaps are widening whilst the dependencies become more acute.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">2.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Detailed analysis of performance data is used to ask questions and arrive at imaginative ways to address the upward pressure on reported crime. When shop theft was on the increase a summit was held to identify creative solutions to business crime. The PCC was a champion for local initiatives developed and delivered by the Middlesbrough Retail Crime Partnership and ‘Redcar Shop Link’ Scheme. Analysis showed a move away from stealing items to sell, to stealing food and essentials. Food banks have been supported and promoted by the PCC where essentials such as groceries and baby formula were the main items stolen. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">2.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">With ‘other theft’ on the increase due to fraud offences, the PCC is taking the opportunity in the run up to Christmas to share fraud prevention advice through a series of public consultation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">roadshows</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in town centres. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">2.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Analysis of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">disproportionate involvement of people with mental health problems held (under section 136) in custody led to a ‘street triage’ approach involving the NHS and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">olice. This has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reduced </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the number</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> detained unnecessarily and the level of reoffending within this cohort, whilst reducing the pressure on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">police resources and allocating the identified mental health need into the correct care pathway. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Other forces are now adopting this approach.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.5</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">When police are called to an address or incident and believe that an individual involved has a mental disorder, learning disability or substance misuse problem, they contact the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mental health </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nurses </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">who</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> carry out an assessment. Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">informs further care planning, ascertaining whether the person needs to be held under s136 and if not, whether follow up from mental health, social or substance misuse services is required. The nursing team refer to those services if required, provide information to service users about relevant agencies and where appropriate, provide follow up appointments within seven days of the assessment.      </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">2.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In depth consultation with vulnerable groups with regard </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a perceived under reporting of hate crime has led to the development of a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Cleveland wide</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">afe </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">laces’ scheme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for vulnerable people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, with major retailers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">being </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">particularly supportive. Feedback uncovered issues for vulnerable people travelling on public transport and therefore the PCC will host a meeting with transport providers to identify preventative solutions. The public profile of the PCC has fostered the ability to bring together a range of partners</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to develop cross </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Cleveland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> initiatives</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and has also aided in engaging with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">private sector </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">at a strategic level to obtain </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Cleveland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> wide support for schemes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">2.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Restorative Justice has been developed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by the PCC working with the force to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">deal with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> crime, anti-social behaviour and ‘conflict’ in communities.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">From 1st April 2013 across </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Cleveland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> most offences of crime, anti-social behaviour and disorder committed by young people under the age of 18, who have not previously come to the attention of the police </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> resolved by way of a Restorative Intervention (RI).</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The RI will usually take place within the community, led by a police officer, PCSO or police staff member and will be swift, effective, sustainable and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">impactive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">2.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Anti Social behaviour, whilst not always resulting in reported crime is of major concern to very many communities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, as evidenced in the visits made by the PCC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. A summit was held to ensure it was on the agenda of every </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">partner within</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the wider CJ family, including housing providers. A particular focus was to ensure that the tragedy of the Fiona Pilkington case would not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">be repeated in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Cleveland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The outcome of the summit ensured social housing providers now work in partnership with police and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">others using the legal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">powers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">available</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. This collaborative approach provides a constructive baseline when dealing with repeat offenders</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> allowing the needs of the perpetrator to be addressed alongside those of the community. The summit also established a training process to identify repeat victims and assess the difference between ASB and hate crime.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">2.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Throughout the first year in office, grappling with CSR10 and then CSR 13 has been a major issue. Working with the Chief Constable and senior staff to develop a policing model that should be sustainable in the longer term, whilst still delivering the 5 priorities of the Police and Crime Plan has been the goal; albeit at a cost of redundancies and compulsory retirements.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3.0</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The role of Commissioners in holding their Chief Constables to account</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A comprehensive programme of accountability sessions is in operation. Each week the PCC and CC meet to deal with emerging and current issues, postbag, complaints, press, IPCC, HMIC. Each month a strategic performance group involving wider police representation goes into detailed performance trends. In addition is a session each month on a rolling programme of Force Performance, Force Financial, Policy and Organisational issues and ‘Partners and Commissioning’. This ensures that crime trends are central to activity, with the involvement of Community Safety Partnerships designed to ensure that all partners are operating in concert, and to provide third party views on police performance.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Chief Constable is required to document key decisions with detailed business cases to be considered by the PCC. These are published, as is a forward work plan. Examples include support to G8 and collaboration agreements. With regard to the latter, the Police and Crime Panel have taken the opportunity to scrutinise the PCCs decision making approach and challenged the decision to send resources to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Northern Ireland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to support G8. The PCC then arranged for Keith Bristow of the National Crime Agency to brief panel members and the PCC on the Strategic Policing Requirement. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Mystery Shoppers and I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ndependent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ustody </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">V</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">isitor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s are employed to report directly to the PCC and so provide independent views of services delivered by the Chief Constable.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4.0</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The division of functions and staff between commissioners and chief constables following the Stage 2 transfers under the Police Reform and Social Responsibility Act 2011;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The following has been submitted to the Home Secretary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Stage 2 Transfer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">As required by the above, please find enclosed documentation. This falls within the ‘maximum transfer’ category. Core staff will be retained by the PCC in order to fulfil the statutory role, plus those staff needed to manage the contractual and ancillary arrangements (with particular regard to the extensive outsourced services), and functions that may not be delegated to the Chief Constable.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The submission details only arrangements for staff, with discussions underway on the future scheme of governance, to be completed well before April. The submission is based on the three principles of setting out clarity of roles, enshrining operational independence for the Chief Constable, and conformance with the Policing Protocol. It allocates staffing to enable the PCC to fulfil the duties of S17 of the Protocol, and the S20 ‘wider responsibility for the enhancement of the delivery of criminal justice’ in Cleveland, without duplication or excessive cost. It does not facilitate any involvement of the PCC in operational policing, with all relevant staff in the employ of the Chief Constable. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">It does not detail any proposed changes to the arrangements for contracts, pensions, estates, assets and liabilities. These require further considerable detailed work which is underway. It is based on the assumption that the issue of pension arrangements, and associated liabilities, for transferred staff will be resolved by April.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.2 Before April arrangements will be in place for resources to be shared between PCC and CC. This will include for example, HR, media, legal. For this reason, the notion of a ‘cost of a PCC’ is of very limited value.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5.0</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The role of commissioners in budget and precept setting;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">5.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The PCC has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">written to the Home Secretary to draw her attention to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Cleveland’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> budget concerns, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">invite</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> her to reconsider future years cuts, and visit Cleveland to se</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e the valuable work going on.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6 local MPs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">were contacted </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for their support.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> A </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">roadshow</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with the Chief constable has been used to inform and consult on the budget.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">5.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The PCC receives detailed assessments from the PCC treasurer and the force before agreeing a budget position and consequent precept assumption. This is refined through </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">stakeholder consultation before discussion with the police and crime panel. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">6.0</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The effectiveness of commissioners in promoting local policing priorities;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.1  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The PCC believes understanding the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">concerns and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">needs of communities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as well </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">specialists across the Criminal Justice sector</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is essential in developing priorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">Your Force</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">Your Voice’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has been the main driver</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for identifying </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">issues</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.   The PCC has attended meetings in all 82 of the wards in Cleveland to hear directly the views of communities.   Meetings have also been held at schools, colleges and local businesses. The PCC has also hosted several web-chats (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">called </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">‘Community Click’)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with the general public and more targeted audience such as young people and the rural community</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  Issues discussed at the meetings are published on the PCC website and quarterly reports are produced which identify key areas for development.  </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">7.0</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Progress on establishing collaboration agreements with other commissioners, policing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> organisations and partners;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">7.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Cleveland collaborate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with Durham and Northumbria on interpreting services. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he three </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">North East Police and Crime Commissioners</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> committed to develop and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">implement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> an integrated regional Violence A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">gainst Women and Girls Strategy. This</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> will ensure that the strategy is incorporated into </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Crime and Policing plans</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">7.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Following concerns raised by rural communities regarding the police response to rural issues, several initiatives have been developed. This has culminated in the PCC joint hosting the North East Rural Crime Conference with the Durham PCC. The event was aimed at police forces and organisations across Cleveland, Durham, North Yorkshire, and Northumbria, and highlighted the progress made since the last conference. This was the first time that Cleveland had hosted the event.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 70.9pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">7.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Criminal Justice Volunteers Fair was held to encourage volunteering</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, not only as special constables, but across</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">all of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> criminal justice. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 70.9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The PCC brought together organisations such as Victim Support, My Sisters Place</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (DV service)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DTV</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Probation Service, CPS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, Unite mediation services,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the Prince’s Trust, and Cleveland Police</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. 16 organisations were represented with some</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">900 potential volunteers identified.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 70.9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The event illustrated how volunteers already make an impact in the criminal justice service as well as highlighting volunteering opportunities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and showing how the various agencies together support an important area</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 71.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The College of Policing noted “The Criminal Justice Volunteer Fair was the first of its type anywhere in England and it was the by far the best example of community and collaborative working.”</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">7.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Give it a Go</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is a project supported by the PCC which aims to disseminate information through Blue Tooth and other technologies on diversionary activities available for young people. The project is being delivered as a co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">llaboration between the Police </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and Teesside University and aims to reduce antisocial behaviour by promoting diversionary activities.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">7.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The PCC has launched annual Cleveland Community Safety Awards to highlight good practice </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in community safety</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The awards were hosted by Teesside University and sponsored by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ousing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">roviders.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">7.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The PCC chairs the core partnership which drives forward the engagement of young people who are classified as NEETs. Talent Match is a 5-year young person led project that will engage, inspire and support 500 young people aged 18-24 from the most deprived wards in Cleveland who have been unemployed for 12 months or more.  By the end of the project, 400 young people will have improved confidence, motivation, self esteem and skills and 100 young people will be supported into employment or enterprise, sustained for 6 months or more. The Project is a collaborative approach to service delivery by the PCC,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Princes Trust, Voluntary Sector, ASDA, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">PD</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Ports, Middlesbrough College.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">8.0</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Transparency of and reporting by commissioners to date.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The website </span><a href="http://www.cleveland.pcc.police.uk"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.cleveland.pcc.police.uk</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">not only facilitates a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">dherence to Specified Information Order</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s but carries far more detail on the operation of the PCC. Some 1000 people visit each month. It provides an in box for those users who need further information. An independent joint audit committee is open to the public, on line ‘community clicks’ are held, a newsletter is produced and public meetings are held across Cleveland. It is disappointing that the media focus is far more likely to be on trivia than on the important work undertaken. Despite the facts being published on the website it is equally disappointing to see media reports of limited accuracy.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There are serious concerns that the desire to have some form of PCC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">comparator tables published will lead to distortion of the facts and diversion from the important issues.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 69pt; text-indent:-33pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The police and crime panel have been assiduous in their scrutiny of PCC actions and this has supported the genuine desire to be open. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">9.0</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Additional information</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">9.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The wider responsibilities of the PCC beyond policing can be illustrated by the drive to improve the coroners service; currently subject to unacceptable delays. A partnership with the local authority, and probation service has provided a roadmap to sustainable improvement. Reflecting on this wider responsibility, the term ‘police and crime commissioner’ should perhaps be replaced by ‘community safety commissioner’.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">9.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Achieving ‘living wage’ accreditation, especially as Cleveland has outsourced so much of its services, is a significant achievement.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">9.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Identifying that because Home Office set firearm licence fees which do not cover costs, they require forces to subsidise licence holders. Ending this subsidy would reduce the need to cut officer numbers.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">9.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Alcohol continues to be a major driver to crime and disorder and a consequent drain on resources across the criminal justice arena. Government failure to move to minimum unit pricing could reduce pressure and assist the public sector in dealing with austerity.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>